included.description:
Â· Co-organize a multidisciplinary year-long series of activities on design anthropology and implications of anthropologically-grounded design for business, government, and non-profit sectors
Â· Conduct independent ethnographic and discourse analytic research on language variation/standardization and identity among communities of sociolinguistic minorities in the United States using audio, video, and internet media
Â· Prepare article and book-length publications based off postdoctoral and dissertation research for multidisciplinary and anthropological venues on language, interaction, and culture (most recent publication was in 2016 in the premier sociolinguistics journal Language in Society)
Â· Present results of research projects at national conferences and through invited talks at multiple universities within and beyond California
included.title: Research Associate

included.description:
Â· Designed and conducted ethnographic research for corporate clients, assisting them in finding ways for branding and differentiating their products and services from a human-centered perspective
Â· Created discussion guides for consumer context labs and field interviews, ethnographic observation guides for field projects, and custom-designed recruitment screeners 
Â· Produced ethnographically-situated insights reports and journey maps to help socialize key takeaway points for business clients on their current and potential consumers and users
Â· Assisted innovation strategists with the creation of toolkits for clients interested in maintaining and sustaining a design thinking organizational culture
Â· Collaborated with innovation strategists for foresight research that aided in innovating products and services with a human-centered approach towards emerging changes in society and culture
Â· Assisted in creating internal security protocols for research data access and storage along with IT specialists
Â· Designed and led client teams in ethnographic immersions to help them understand the perspective of their consumers/users
Â· Created and evaluated new research offerings for the consumer insights division that incorporated linguistic anthropology/ethnography of communication methods
Â· Co-authored white papers for business development that incorporate social science theories and concepts with ramifications for brand differentiation and strategy
Â· Developed and co-authored project proposals for business development with strategists and other key leaders in the agency
Â· Clients included AT&T, Proctor & Gamble, HTC, and FedEx
included.title: Resident Anthropologist

included.description:
Â· Design, recruit for, and conduct in-person and remote usability research sessions with TripIt end users, with expertise in Rapid Iterative Testing and Evaluation (RITE), exploratory/ethnographic research, conventional usability testing, concept testing, video diaries, and card sorting for information architecture
Â· Conduct research for both the web application and the native mobile apps on iOS and Android
Â· Create and manage the research participant panel for TripIt to ensure we have a diverse and inclusive representation of users to yield inspiring insights from research sessions and increase accessibility across differently-abled users
Â· Craft actionable and human-centric insights reports, videos, and presentations to socialize findings for various business units (product, marketing, business development)
Â· Facilitate design thinking workshops with cross-functional teams to evangelize the process across projects and beyond research (i.e., ideation/brainstorming workshops inspired by research)
Â· Organize company-wide roundtables and workshops on new tools and techniques that expand user research methodologies
Â· Write and disseminate a company-wide user research newsletter to socialize the importance of user experience research as part of innovation
Â· Completed trainings on design thinking workshop coaching across project stages, presenting complex information, presenting with impact, and storytelling for business impact
Â· Took courses to supplement conventional user experience research techniques, such as questionnaire design for social surveys and fundamental quantitative analysis using R
Â· Engage continuously in company-provided and external diversity and inclusion trainings to enhance team collaboration and increase product innovation (e.g., applying insights on accessibility to enhance features and functionality)

included.summary: I am a design anthropologist who works as a part of an in-house product team for a high-tech company and previously conducted research as a consultant for Fortune 500 companies to discover new and hidden opportunities for emerging human and cultural problems. As an advocate of design-led innovation, I thrive in creating innovative products and features from a human-centered perspective, and I actively seek out collaboration with multidisciplinary teams, including user experience designers, developers, and marketing specialists, to drive innovation. I am also passionate about diversity and inclusion in high tech, participating in many corporate, academic, and community events to increase different perspectives and backgrounds in the industry to inspire teams to create sustainable, profitable, and desirable solutions for users/consumers and the business.

included.description: As a member of this multidisciplinary team consisting of public health experts, psychiatrists, and counselors, I served as a voluntary anthropological consultant and interviewer on this project. Part of my responsibilities included helping to design interview questions that were culturally relevant to and sociolinguistically-appropriate for boys and men of color (primarily African American); reviewing data from focus groups that contributed to the construction of a screener and set of tools for boys/young men of color to manage symptoms of trauma in their everyday lives; and collecting data on the use of the screener and lifestyle toolkit for the population under study.

New Faculty Majority Foundation's mission is to educate the public about the impact of the contingent faculty crisis on educational quality and the public good, and to mobilize a broad coalition of constituencies to support ethical reform. As a 501(c)3 public charity, the NFM Foundation engages in research, education and advocacy to improve the quality of higher education by improving the working conditions of the majority of its faculty. The NFM Foundation has received support from The Marguerite Casey Foundation, The Ford Foundation, The French American Charitable Trust, The Rockefeller Foundation, The Discount Foundation, and The Tides Foundation. 

- See more at: http://www.newfacultymajority.info/equity/nfm-foundation#sthash.6Z8qJPpY.dpuf
